solutions.content:
**Iterative**
**time:** `O(N)`; **space:** `O(1)`

In this solution I maintain two least numbers in an array that have remainder `1` modulo `3` and two least numbers that have remainder `2` modulo `3`.
Actually this is done using `dp`'ish algo (as it is done step by step using previously obtained two least numbers) but this algo is different from [lee215](https://leetcode.com/problems/greatest-sum-divisible-by-three/discuss/431077/JavaC%2B%2BPython-One-Pass-O(1)-space)'s `dp` solution.
```
int maxSumDivThree(vector<int>& n)
{
	int out{}, m1{10000}, mm1{10001}, m2{10000}, mm2{10001};
	for(const auto & i : n)
	{
		out += i;
		if(i%3==1)
			mm1 = i<=m1 ? exchange(m1,i) : i<mm1 ? i : mm1;
		else if(i%3==2)
			mm2 = i<=m2 ? exchange(m2,i) : i<mm2 ? i : mm2;
	}
	return out -= out%3==1 ? min(m1, mm2+m2) : out%3==2 ? min(m2, mm1+m1) : 0;
}
```

**Explanation**

Sum up all the numbers and determine two least numbers equal `1 mod 3` and two least numbers equal `2 mod 3`. If the total sum is `1 mod 3` you should substract either the least `1 mod 3` number or two least `2 mod 3` numbers. If the total sum is `1 mod 3` you should substract either the least `2 mod 3` number or two least `1 mod 3` numbers.
Note, that
```mm1 = i<=m1 ? exchange(m1,i) : i<mm1 ? i : mm1;```
and 
```mm2 = i<=m2 ? exchange(m2,i) : i<mm2 ? i : mm2;```
calculate the aforementioned two least numbers using `exchange` magic.

**Notation**

`m1` - least number that is `1 mod 3`;
`mm1` - second to least number that is `1 mod 3`;
`m2` - least number that is `2 mod 3`;
`mm2` - second to least number that is `2 mod 3`.

**[lee215](https://leetcode.com/problems/greatest-sum-divisible-by-three/discuss/431077/JavaC%2B%2BPython-One-Pass-O(1)-space)'s solution**
**time:** `O(N)`; **space:** `O(1)`
```
int maxSumDivThree(vector<int>& A)
{
	int dp[3]{}, t[3]{};
	for(const int & a : A)
		for(copy(begin(dp), end(dp), begin(t)); const int & i : t)
			dp[(i+a)%3] = max(dp[(i+a)%3], i+a);
	return dp[0];
}
```
**Notation**

`dp[0]` - largest sum that is `0 mod 3`;
`dp[1]` - largest sum that is `1 mod 3`;
`dp[2]` - largest sum  that is `2 mod 3`.

In order to find the best `0 mod 3` sum at the end we need to track the best sums of three  `modulo 3` categories
* best `0 mod 3` sum (naturally);
* best `1 mod 3` sum;
* best `2 mod 3` sum.

We should consider new element "added" to each of the "best sums".

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/54b3d9bd-a2b9-4ed1-a50a-90ae31c08d02_1638444975.8460197.png)

And each of them *can* become the best sum of another (or the same) `modulo 3` category.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/cf735d65-3e8d-4c88-905a-20914f9c66a7_1638444811.8744032.png)

So we should find out which of this possibilities happens to maintain the best sums.

